The exam blueprint, and where each module fits.

The solutions architect associate exam has four domains, weighted roughly equally, so you shouldn't over-study one. Designing secure architectures is the largest at about thirty percent, drawing on the identity, security-services, and networking modules. Designing resilient architectures is next, drawing on compute, databases, and the disaster-recovery module. Designing high-performing architectures draws on compute, serverless, storage, the edge module, and the data and integration modules. And designing cost-optimized architectures draws on the cost levers, the storage classes, and instance choice.

The foundations module and the observability module cut across all four domains, and this final module is the integration; there's no exam topic not covered somewhere in the previous thirteen.

The two hardest domains tend to be resilient architectures and secure architectures, for the same reason: each has several services that look similar, and a question often hinges on one small distinguishing constraint, like multi-zone versus a read replica, or which encryption option the scenario demands.
